According to the [[w:documentary hypothesis|documentary hypothesis]], the [[w:Torah|Torah]] is composed from a number of originally independant sources joined by a [[w:redaction|redactor]]. One of these supposed sources is named the [[w:Deuteronomist|"Deuteronomist"]], due to it composing the vast majority of the text of [[w:Deuteronomy|Deuteronomy]]. 

In the documentary hypothesis this source is believed to have been written in two editions, the second edition making changes so that it explained how king [[w:Josiah|Josiah]]'s positive qualities failed to prevent God from punishing Judah via the [[w:Babylonian Empire|Babylonian Empire]] after Josiah's death. The bulk of the changes thought to have been added to the text in the second edition are threats by God to destroy Judah and Israel for excessive idolatry, and promises to restore Judah and Israel from such destruction if they repent.

''The numbering does not necessarily reflect that in the original source, but instead exists simply to make life easier for the modern reader''

